	1939: The Alliance That Never Was and the Coming of World War II

	By Micheal Jabara Carley

	The British Conservative government hoped to avoid war, not so much by deterrence as by appeasement. Of course, appeasement did not have, by certain British lights anyway, the craven, negative connotations we now associate with the world; it meant a reasonable effort to meet Adolf Hitler's "legitimate" grievances for revision of the Versailles treaty which had settled the First World War.


