	CE: Well it’s interesting. For a long time the United States has not cared much, or not appeared to care very much, about its capacity in the Arctic. ...But there’s been a sort of crescendo for the last couple of years, people saying “Well, Canada’s getting interested, Russia’s getting interested. What’s the U.S. doing?” And the answer to that question has been: not very much.

	...That may have been a wakeup call within the Coast Guard that the U.S. doesn’t have very much capacity

 	...I think it’s interesting to note the extraordinary disparity between the number of ice breakers that for example Russia has and the U.S.

